            {
              "lessonId": "recXQvzmdMt6O0m83",
              "termNumber": 3,
              "termLabel": "Term 3",
              "weekNumber": 26,
              "weekLabel": "Week 2",
              "sequence": 26,
              "lessonLabel": "Lesson 26",
              "title": "25m Canadian Government: Grade 7 - Lesson 26",
              "body": "Federal Government\n\n➜ INTRO\nCanada is divided into electoral districts, each one represented by a Member of Parliament (MP). These districts are also called ridings or\nconstituencies. Because these areas are determined by population rather than area, some can be geographically very large while others are smaller.\nToday, you are going to do some research about your local federal electoral district. By using the resources below, and through additional\nresearch with help from your parent or teacher, see if you can answer the following questions:\nHow many electoral districts are there in Canada?\nWhat is the name of your local electoral district?\nCan you find a map of it?\nWho is your MP?\nWhat party do they belong to?\nWho were the other candidates in the most recent election?\nWhat percentage of the vote did each candidate receive?\nCan you find out more information about your MP from their own website?\n\n➜ VIEW\n∞ Video Link: Who are parliamentarians?\n∞ Link: Home Page for the 2025 Federal Election\n\n➜ EXPLORE\n∞ Link: Activity: Parliament and Elections",
              "teacherNotes": "",
