              "lessonId": "recagkvauMMlvtdp1",
              "termNumber": 3,
              "termLabel": "Term 3",
              "weekNumber": 28,
              "weekLabel": "Week 4",
              "sequence": 28,
              "lessonLabel": "Lesson 28",
              "title": "25m Canadian Government: Grade 7 - Lesson 28",
              "body": "➜ READ & NARRATE\nFind a current events article about the federal government. Narrate your chosen article either orally or written.",
              "teacherNotes": "",
              "editUrl": "https://airtable.com/apphTWdjAdJEcAmoe/pago27hsdn3q8TtGK?XRKkD=recIVyFFuzbJhFIAy&6J82c=recagkvauMMlvtdp1",
              "links": []
            },
            {
              "lessonId": "recTQ67xGPzu9P8Yl",
              "termNumber": 3,
              "termLabel": "Term 3",
              "weekNumber": 29,
              "weekLabel": "Week 5",
              "sequence": 29,
              "lessonLabel": "Lesson 29",
              "title": "25m Canadian Government: Grade 7 - Lesson 29",
              "body": "Provincial Government\n\n➜ INTRO\nEach province and territory has a legislative assembly, forming the provincial level of government. Each province and territory is divided into electoral districts with a representative to the legislative assembly from each district. The boundaries of your provincial electoral district may differ from the federal one. The provincial representative have difference titles in different provinces/territories (e.g. Member of Provincial Parliament (MPP) in Ontario, Members of the National Assembly (MNA) in Quebec, and Members of the Legislative Assembly (MLA) in most other places). The leader of the party with the most seats becomes the premier.\nEach province also has a Lieutenant Governor who, like the Governor General, is the representative of the King of Canada for each province and territory.\nToday, you are going to do some research about your local provincial electoral district. By using the resources below, and through additional research with help from your parent or teacher, see if you can answer the following questions:\nWho is the premier of your province/territory and what is their political party?\nWhat is the name of your local provincial electoral district?\nCan you find a map of it?\nWho is your representative, and what title do they have in your province/territory?\nWhat party do they belong to?\nWhen was the most recent election?\nWho were the other candidates in the most recent election?\nWhat percentage of the vote did each candidate receive?\nCan you find out more information about your representative from their own website?\nWho is your Lieutenant Governor and how long have they served in this role?\n\n➜ VIEW\nFind the Elections website for your home province or territory (use search terms \"election\" and name of province/territory)",
              "teacherNotes": "",
              "editUrl": "https://airtable.com/apphTWdjAdJEcAmoe/pago27hsdn3q8TtGK?XRKkD=recIVyFFuzbJhFIAy&6J82c=recTQ67xGPzu9P8Yl",
              "links": []
            },
            {
              "lessonId": "recLoLeMcR8VaWem4",
              "termNumber": 3,
              "termLabel": "Term 3",
              "weekNumber": 30,
              "weekLabel": "Week 6",
              "sequence": 30,
              "lessonLabel": "Lesson 30",
              "title": "25m Canadian Government: Grade 7 - Lesson 30",
              "body": "➜ READ & NARRATE\nFind a current events article about your provincial or territorial government. Narrate your chosen article either orally or written.",
              "teacherNotes": "",
              "editUrl": "https://airtable.com/apphTWdjAdJEcAmoe/pago27hsdn3q8TtGK?XRKkD=recIVyFFuzbJhFIAy&6J82c=recLoLeMcR8VaWem4",
              "links": []
            },
            {
              "lessonId": "recjg7jgCGh0AB6aQ",
              "termNumber": 3,
              "termLabel": "Term 3",
              "weekNumber": 31,
              "weekLabel": "Week 7",
              "sequence": 31,
              "lessonLabel": "Lesson 31",
              "title": "25m Canadian Government: Grade 7 - Lesson 31",
              "body": "Local Government\n\n➜ INTRO\nToday, you will look at local government. Local governments are a paradox, because we most often forget that they exist, while they often\nhave the most direct impact on our daily lives. \nThe head the of the municipal government is usually called a mayor, but may have a different title in some places. Your municipality might be the same as your city, or, for smaller towns and rural areas, the municipality might be made up of several communities or a wider area. With a the help of a parent or teacher look up the website for your municipality and try to answer the following questions:\nWhat is the name of your municipality?\nCan you find a map of it?\nWho is the mayor (or other title) of your municipality?\nWhat other representatives make up your local government and what are their titles?\nWhen was the most recent election?\nWho were the other candidates in the most recent election?\nWhat percentage of the vote did each candidate receive?\nCan you find out more information about your mayor from their own website?",
              "teacherNotes": "",
              "editUrl": "https://airtable.com/apphTWdjAdJEcAmoe/pago27hsdn3q8TtGK?XRKkD=recIVyFFuzbJhFIAy&6J82c=recjg7jgCGh0AB6aQ",
